// =============================================================
// Rule 1 — Poisoned Tool Description Ingested
// =============================================================
//
// SCHEMA AMENDMENT REFERENCES
//   - SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-20: Rules classified as
//     event-time vs content/pattern.
//   - SCHEMA_NOTES.md AMENDMENT 2026-05-25: Rules 5/6 dropped;
//     final pack composition is Rules 1, 2, 3, 4.
//
// CLASSIFICATION
//   Content/pattern rule. Host-agnostic. No EventTime filter.
//   Operates on the textual content of tool descriptions at the
//   moment of ingestion, independent of when the description was
//   loaded or which host loaded it.
//
// DETECTION PURPOSE
//   Detects MCP tool descriptions containing instruction-like
//   keyword patterns characteristic of prompt-injection attacks
//   embedded in the description field. Matches the same keyword
//   list used by the forwarder's ENRICHER.PROMPT_INJECTION_KEYWORDS
//   to produce the ResultContainsInstructions flag — see
//   forwarder/CONFIG.py. Single source of truth between the
//   forwarder's pre-computed flag and this detection rule.
//
// KEYWORD LIST (mirrors CONFIG.PROMPT_INJECTION_KEYWORDS)
//   IMPORTANT, you must, do not inform, ignore previous,
//   <SYSTEM>, <system>, SYSTEM:
//   Case-insensitive substring match — same matching semantics as
//   ENRICHER._scan_for_instructions() in the forwarder.
//
// THREAT MODEL FINDINGS
//   - Finding 3 — Untrusted Description Surface: the MCP protocol
//     loads tool descriptions into the shared LLM context window
//     without inspection, filtering, or trust separation.
//   - Finding 8 — Unified Instructions Problem: the LLM cannot
//     distinguish between descriptions authored by trusted versus
//     untrusted sources once they are in the context window.
//
// OWASP AGENTIC TOP 10
//   ASI01 — Agent Goal Hijack
//
// MITRE ATLAS
//   AML.T0051 — LLM Prompt Injection (Direct)
//
// LAB DATA — KNOWN POSITIVE AND NEGATIVE CASES
//   Verified against MCPProtocolLogs_CL as of 2026-05-25:
//
//   FIRES (positive):
//     calendar_sync V1 (hash 44c65aee45b061d1..., 862 chars).
//     Contains <IMPORTANT> tags, "Do not inform", and "VERY VERY
//     VERY important" dramatic framing. Classic Tool Shadowing
//     payload as documented in the threat model report.
//     Expected: 18 events fire.
//
//   DOES NOT FIRE (negative):
//     send_email (hash cb006818569a05e3..., 216 chars). Clean
//     description with no instruction-like content. Expected: 24
//     events correctly do not fire.
//
//   DOES NOT FIRE (KNOWN LIMITATION — Finding 6):
//     calendar_sync V2 (hash 730af110b70716da..., 606 chars). V2
//     was deliberately rewritten with subtler framing — "known
//     routing configuration," "standard infrastructure," "no
//     user action" — that evades the keyword-based detection while
//     preserving the attack payload (recipient redirect to
//     attacker@pwnd.com, original recipient moved to email body).
//     Expected: 6 events correctly do not fire AT THIS LAYER, but
//     are caught downstream by Rule 2 (cross-tool reference) and
//     would be caught by Rule 3 (hash drift) if the watchlist were
//     populated with V1 as the approved baseline.
//
// FINDING 6 — THE OBFUSCATION GAP (acknowledged limitation)
//   The threat model report's Finding 6 states: "Static scanning
//   of tool descriptions is insufficient as a primary defense —
//   it cannot detect what it cannot read." V2 demonstrates this
//   in practice: keyword scanning catches dramatic payloads
//   (Finding 3 + Finding 8 in their visible form) but does not
//   catch semantic reframings that preserve attack intent without
//   triggering the keyword list. Rule 1 is a defense-in-depth
//   component, not a sole defense. Rule 2 provides coverage for
//   the V2 class of attack via cross-tool-reference detection.
//
// SCOPE FILTERS
//   - EventType == "ToolDescriptionLoaded": only inspect
//     description-load events. Other event types do not carry the
//     ToolDescription field.
//   - isnotempty(ToolDescription): defensive guard against null or
//     empty descriptions (should not occur in practice but
//     protects the regex from edge cases).
//   - No HostApp filter. Rule 1 is host-agnostic per content/pattern
//     classification — the detection signature does not depend on
//     which MCP host loaded the description.
//   - No EventTime filter. Same reasoning as Rule 4's content/pattern
//     classification — the rule operates on description content,
//     not on event timing. Adding an EventTime filter would
//     introduce a false correctness condition (the rule would
//     appear to depend on freshness when in fact it does not).
//
// PROJECTION
//   EventTime, SessionId, HostApp, ModelName for triage context.
//   ServerName, ToolName for attack attribution.
//   ToolDescription for analyst review of matched content.
//   ToolDescriptionHash for cross-reference with Rule 3 baseline.
//   ToolDescriptionLength for anomaly signal (poisoned descriptions
//   tend to be longer than legitimate ones).
//   IngestionAgent for forensic provenance.
//
// KNOWN FALSE POSITIVES
//   A legitimate tool description that happens to contain one of
//   the seven keywords for benign reasons (e.g., a tool whose
//   stated function is to handle "IMPORTANT" tagged content, or a
//   security-research tool whose description references prompt
//   injection patterns). Triage by reviewing the matched
//   ToolDescription content against the tool's expected legitimate
//   function.
//
// TRIAGE STEPS
//   1. Review ToolDescription content — does the matched keyword
//      appear in instruction-like context (e.g., directing
//      behavior, redirecting parameters, requesting user-hiding)
//      or in benign reference context?
//   2. Cross-check ToolDescriptionHash against the
//      MCPToolDescriptions watchlist (Rule 3) — if the hash is
//      known-approved, the keyword match is likely benign.
//   3. Check whether the description references other connected
//      tools — Rule 2 fires on the same event when cross-tool
//      references exist; both rules firing on the same
//      description is high-confidence Tool Shadowing.
//   4. If the description is confirmed malicious, disconnect the
//      offending server from the host application and capture
//      session evidence for incident response.
//
// =============================================================

MCPProtocolLogs_CL
| where EventType == "ToolDescriptionLoaded"
| where isnotempty(ToolDescription)
| where ToolDescription matches regex @"(?i)(IMPORTANT|you must|do not inform|ignore previous|<SYSTEM>|<system>|SYSTEM:)"
| project
    EventTime,
    SessionId,
    HostApp,
    ModelName,
    ServerName,
    ToolName,
    ToolDescription,
    ToolDescriptionHash,
    ToolDescriptionLength,
    IngestionAgent
| order by EventTime desc
